I originally had the standard `count_box = [0]` trick, which I can
reinstate. You can’t just store the value on `foo` itself because that
will refer to the wrapped `LazyModule`; i.e., using

```python
    @lazy.lazy_load("foo")
    def foo():
      foo.counter = getattr(foo, "counter", 0) + 1
      return EqualToEverything()
```

raises “Circular import when resolving LazyModule 'foo'”. You can get around this with

```python
    @lazy.lazy_load("foo")
    def foo():
      foo.counter += 1
      return EqualToEverything()
    foo.counter = 0
```

but given that it’s this subtle I’m inclined to stick to the much
simpler close-over-`[0]`, which is at least somewhat idiomatic.

I think one or two dataloaders is the most common cases.

But maybe we can detect all dataloaders automatically here, e.g.
```python
def new_func(model, optimizer, *inner_args, **inner_kwargs):
    class DecoratedTorchNano(TorchNano):
        def train(self):
            _model, _optimizer = self.setup(model, optmizer)
            
            # setup all dataloaders automatically
            inner_args=list(inner_args)
            for idx, arg in enumerate(inner_args):
                if isinstance(arg, DataLoader):
                    inner_args[idx] = self.setup_dataloaders(arg)
            for key, value in inner_kwargs.items():
                if isintance(value, DataLoader):
                    inner_kwargs[key] = self.setup_dataloaders(value)
            
            return func(_model, _optimizer, *inner_args, **inner_kwargs)
```
And we can give a warning if we don't find dataloader in the arguments.

We can even use the this methods to detect model and optimizers automatically, so that we can support any parameter list, as long as model, optimizers and dataloaders are all in parameter list. But it might be too complicated to do so.

