To get the value out of the struct, I decided to opt for an explicit conversion operator that converts the enum type to its underlying type (in this case `string`), rather than have a `Value` property (or something else).

This makes getting the underlying value consistent with normal enums that are built-in to the language, e.g.:

```c#
int four = (int)ContainerSize.FourInch;
string red = (string)ContainerColor.Red;
```

I think it would be fine to remove the whole block, including `array_iterator `:

```cpp
template  <class T>
using array_iterator = typename std::add_pointer<T>::type;

template <class T>
array_iterator<T> array_begin(const buffer_info& buffer) {
    return array_iterator<T>(reinterpret_cast<T*>(buffer.ptr));
}

template <class T>
array_iterator<T> array_end(const buffer_info& buffer) {
    return array_iterator<T>(reinterpret_cast<T*>(buffer.ptr) + buffer.size);
}
```

